{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Before you can embed a document and store it in a vector database, you must split it into chunks. Each chunk becomes one vector — the unit of retrieval. The chunking strategy you choose directly determines retrieval quality: chunks that are too large dilute the signal with unrelated content; chunks that are too small lose the surrounding context that gives sentences meaning. This document covers the three main strategies — fixed-size, recursive, and semantic — and the engineering decisions within each."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three chunking strategies compared side by side: Fixed-size splits every N tokens with overlap M (simple, may split mid-sentence, best for structured data/code); Recursive splits on paragraph then sentence then word boundaries (respects natural structure, best for prose/markdown); Semantic splits where sentence embedding similarity drops (matches topic shifts, best for long heterogeneous docs). Bottom section shows why overlap matters: without it a sentence split at a boundary loses context; with 20% overlap the retrieved chunk carries context from its neighbours."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fixed-Size Chunking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fixed-size chunking splits a document into windows of exactly "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "chunk_size"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tokens with a configurable "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "overlap"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of tokens shared between consecutive chunks. It is the simplest and fastest method, and it is the right default for structured text (code, CSV, JSON lines) where natural boundaries are either absent or meaningless."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import tiktoken\n\ndef fixed_chunks(\n    text: str,\n    chunk_size: int = 512,\n    overlap: int = 64,\n    model: str = \"cl100k_base\",   # tokeniser used by most embedding models\n) -> list[str]:\n    enc = tiktoken.get_encoding(model)\n    tokens = enc.encode(text)\n    chunks = []\n    start = 0\n    while start < len(tokens):\n        end = min(start + chunk_size, len(tokens))\n        chunk_tokens = tokens[start:end]\n        chunks.append(enc.decode(chunk_tokens))\n        if end == len(tokens):\n            break\n        start += chunk_size - overlap   # slide window by (chunk_size - overlap)\n    return chunks\n\n\n# Example\ntext = open(\"large_doc.txt\").read()\nchunks = fixed_chunks(text, chunk_size=512, overlap=64)\nprint(f\"{len(chunks)} chunks, first: {chunks[0][:80]}...\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "overlap"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter prevents context loss at boundaries. A sentence that straddles two chunk boundaries will appear in full in at least one of them. A rule of thumb is 10–20% of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "chunk_size"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": for 512-token chunks, use 50–100 tokens of overlap."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Recursive Chunking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Recursive chunking tries each separator in a priority list — paragraph break, then sentence end, then whitespace — and only descends to finer granularity when the current chunk exceeds "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "chunk_size"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This produces chunks that respect the natural structure of the text, avoiding splits in the middle of a sentence or a bullet point."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import re, tiktoken\n\nSEPARATORS = [\n    \"\\n\\n\",   # paragraph\n    \"\\n\",     # line\n    \". \",     # sentence\n    \"? \",\n    \"! \",\n    \", \",     # clause\n    \" \",      # word\n    \"\",       # character (last resort)\n]\n\ndef _token_len(text: str, enc) -> int:\n    return len(enc.encode(text))\n\ndef recursive_chunks(\n    text: str,\n    chunk_size: int = 512,\n    overlap: int = 64,\n    separators: list[str] = SEPARATORS,\n    model: str = \"cl100k_base\",\n) -> list[str]:\n    enc = tiktoken.get_encoding(model)\n\n    def split(text: str, seps: list[str]) -> list[str]:\n        if not seps or _token_len(text, enc) <= chunk_size:\n            return [text]\n        sep = seps[0]\n        parts = text.split(sep) if sep else list(text)\n        chunks, current = [], \"\"\n        for part in parts:\n            candidate = current + (sep if current else \"\") + part\n            if _token_len(candidate, enc) <= chunk_size:\n                current = candidate\n            else:\n                if current:\n                    chunks.extend(split(current, seps[1:]))\n                current = part\n        if current:\n            chunks.extend(split(current, seps[1:]))\n        return chunks\n\n    raw = split(text, separators)\n\n    # Apply overlap by carrying tokens from the previous chunk\n    result, carry = [], \"\"\n    for chunk in raw:\n        if carry:\n            chunk = carry + \" \" + chunk\n        tokens = enc.encode(chunk)\n        if len(tokens) > chunk_size:\n            # Should not happen after recursive split, but guard anyway\n            chunk = enc.decode(tokens[:chunk_size])\n            tokens = tokens[:chunk_size]\n        result.append(chunk)\n        carry = enc.decode(tokens[-overlap:]) if overlap else \"\"\n    return result"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LangChain's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " implements this pattern. The implementation above makes the tokenisation explicit so you control exactly how many tokens each chunk contains — useful when your embedding model has a hard context limit (512 or 8192 tokens depending on the model)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Semantic Chunking"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Semantic chunking embeds each sentence individually and splits where consecutive sentence similarity drops below a threshold. It produces chunks that correspond to coherent topic segments, regardless of paragraph boundaries. The trade-off is cost: you embed every sentence of the source document, not just the chunks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef cosine_similarity(a: list[float], b: list[float]) -> float:\n    a, b = np.array(a), np.array(b)\n    return float(np.dot(a, b) / (np.linalg.norm(a) * np.linalg.norm(b) + 1e-10))\n\ndef split_sentences(text: str) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Naive sentence splitter — replace with spacy for production.\"\"\"\n    import re\n    return [s.strip() for s in re.split(r'(?<=[.!?])\\s+', text) if s.strip()]\n\ndef semantic_chunks(\n    text: str,\n    embed_fn,           # callable: list[str] -> list[list[float]]\n    threshold: float = 0.75,\n    min_chunk_sentences: int = 2,\n) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Split text into topic-coherent chunks.\n    embed_fn should batch sentences for efficiency.\n    threshold: cosine similarity below which a split is inserted.\n    \"\"\"\n    sentences = split_sentences(text)\n    if len(sentences) < 2:\n        return [text]\n\n    embeddings = embed_fn(sentences)\n\n    # Compute similarity between consecutive sentences\n    sims = [\n        cosine_similarity(embeddings[i], embeddings[i + 1])\n        for i in range(len(embeddings) - 1)\n    ]\n\n    # Insert split points where similarity drops below threshold\n    chunks, current = [], [sentences[0]]\n    for i, sim in enumerate(sims):\n        if sim < threshold and len(current) >= min_chunk_sentences:\n            chunks.append(\" \".join(current))\n            current = [sentences[i + 1]]\n        else:\n            current.append(sentences[i + 1])\n    if current:\n        chunks.append(\" \".join(current))\n    return chunks\n\n\n# Usage with Cohere (Anthropic has no public embeddings API)\nimport cohere\nco = cohere.Client(\"your-key\")\n\ndef embed(texts: list[str]) -> list[list[float]]:\n    resp = co.embed(texts=texts, model=\"embed-english-v3.0\",\n                    input_type=\"search_document\")\n    return resp.embeddings\n\nchunks = semantic_chunks(long_document_text, embed_fn=embed, threshold=0.75)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
